<paragraph blockId="28.[192,1441,1708,1860]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">
Species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hope" authorityYear="1837" box="[364,493,1709,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Megaceras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[364,493,1709,1732]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">Megaceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are characterized by tridentate protibiae, frons with a single horn in the males or a single tubercle in the females, prosternal process present, smooth elytra, and mandibles distinctly bidentate and exposed. Little is known of the life history of these beetles. Adults are active at night and the larvae probably live in rotten wood or in soil feeding on organic matter (
<bibRefCitation author="Ratcliffe, B. C." box="[1117,1294,1804,1828]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" pagination="1 - 506" refId="ref27385" refString="Ratcliffe, B. C. 2003. The Dynastinae scarab beetles of Costa Rica and Panama. Bulletin of the University of Nebraska State Museum 16: 1 - 506." type="journal article" year="2003">Ratcliffe 2003</bibRefCitation>
). The genus contains 19 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Endrodi, S." box="[433,598,1836,1860]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" refId="ref25005" refString="Endrodi, S. 1985. The Dynastinae of the World. Dr W. Junk; Dordrecht, Netherlands. 800 p." type="book" year="1985">Endrödi 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dechambre, R. - P." box="[608,813,1836,1860]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" pagination="123 - 128" refId="ref24409" refString="Dechambre, R. - P. 1981. Nouvelles especes de Dynastidae de la region Neotropicale [Coleoptera Scarabaeoidea]. Revue Francaise d'Entomologie (N. S.) 3: 123 - 128." type="journal article" year="1981">Dechambre 1981</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dechambre, R. - P." box="[823,901,1836,1860]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" pagination="192" refId="ref24521" refString="Dechambre, R. - P. 1998 b. Megaceras brevis n. sp., une nouvelle espece de Dynastidae du Perou (Co. Scarabaeoidea). Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France 103: 192." type="journal article" year="1998">1998b</bibRefCitation>
,c; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ratcliffe, B. C." box="[928,1094,1836,1860]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" pagination="463 - 467" refId="ref27417" refString="Ratcliffe, B. C. 2007. A remarkable new species of Megaceras from Peru (Scarabaeidae: Dynastinae: Oryctini). The &quot; Dim Effect &quot;: nature mimicking art. The Coleopterists Bulletin 61 (3): 463 - 467." type="journal article" year="2007">Ratcliffe 2007</bibRefCitation>
) with distribution in Central
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[192,1440,195,251]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
America and South America, where 6 species are known from 
<collectingCountry box="[938,1016,195,219]" name="Brazil" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Brazil</collectingCountry>
; four of them occur in the Brazilian Amazon.
</paragraph>
